article.headline: San Antonio wins sixth straight
article.linkText: Spurs beat Rockets for 2nd time in 3 days
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs didn't need Tim Duncan to score to beat Houston for the second time in three days. Manu Ginobili scored 16 points and Tony Parker had 14 points and 12 assists to help the Spurs beat the Rockets 86-73 on Saturday night. Duncan had a season-low eight points on 2-for-10 shooting, but had 12 rebounds. "It was important for us to let him rest a little bit," Ginobili said. Duncan sat out the whole fourth quarter. The victory was the Spurs' sixth straight and lifted the defending NBA champions within a half-game of Midwest Division-leading Dallas. "We might have played our best game so far, against a very good team," said Spurs coach Gregg Popovich, whose team never trailed in the contest. "Houston is competitive and they play great defense." The Rockets' defenders had trouble keeping up with the fleet Spurs early on, but Houston's offense struggled even more. Less than three minutes into the game, Rasho Nesterovic (14 points) made his third basket. That was one more field goal than the entire Rockets team managed in the opening period. After one, Houston trailed 21-8. "That set us back for the whole game," said Houston point guard Steve Francis, who led his team with 17 points on 5-for-17 shooting. It was the second time in as many games that the Rockets had been held to only eight points in a quarter by the Spurs. On Thursday, it was the second period in a game that set a modern-day NBA record low for scoring in a first half (55). "I don't think it was just one thing that contributed to us losing," Rockets coach Jeff Van Gundy said. "We are in a bad way right now. ... We have to rebuild the foundation of our team." Yao Ming and Jim Jackson each had 11 points for Houston. The Rockets trailed by as much as 16 in the first half, but they found themselves within striking distance at 48-41 midway through the third quarter. Bruce Bowen made a 3-pointer and a 14-footer on San Antonio's next two possessions to set off a 14-4 run, capped by a short jumper by Robert Horry that gave the Spurs a 63-45 lead. The Rockets didn't get any closer than 11 points after that. Houston shot 2-for-13 in the opening period. Cuttino Mobley made a 14-footer from the right corner at 9:08 and Maurice Taylor scored on a putback about six minutes later. Ginobili hit a 3-pointer for the first points of the second quarter, but Yao followed that with a 3-point play to start a 14-3 run that pulled the Rockets to 27-22 at 6:47. Houston got to 34-31 on a 3-pointer by Jackson at 2:09, and got the ball back on a steal by Mobley. But Yao missed a 5-foot hook, and San Antonio finished with a layup by Bowen and Duncan's only basket of the half, a 17-footer at the buzzer to make the score 40-33.

Game notes
The Spurs have beaten Houston five straight overall and 12 straight at home. ... San Antonio's Malik Rose missed his sixth consecutive game with a strained tendon in his right ankle. ... Francis is three assists and 16 rebounds short of 2,000 in both categories. He had five of each Saturday ... The Rockets are 1-5 when scoring less than 80 points.
